News reader by Matthias Kunz¶

This notebook contains the code to scrape different news pages to build a recommender system based on a user specified question. The system is built for usage of german language and german news pages.

Data acquisition¶

At first, the news articles have to be scraped. Unfortunately, some of the newspapers or news agencies do not offer a complete list of news articles. And also the main website of some is not supported by newspaper3k. Therefore a small trick is done. Using the google news website, a search for articles of a specified newspaper is done. The search is done on a interval but the search interval can be freely chosen. In this example only german articles are searched.

The search returns an xml including all the links to the articles and the publishing dates. Afterwards, the newspaper package is used to download also the title and the content of the article. Invalid links are excluded.

# defining the timeframe from when the news pages should be gathered
# monthly base but not fine enough for daily newspapers ~30 articles / day -> 300/month but google just gets 100
start_dates = [datetime.strftime(dt, "%Y-%m-%d") for dt in rrule(MONTHLY, dtstart=datetime(2022, 1, 1), until=datetime(2022, 6, 1))]
end_dates = [datetime.strftime(dt, "%Y-%m-%d") for dt in rrule(MONTHLY, dtstart=datetime(2022, 1, 31), bymonthday=(31, -1), bysetpos=1, until=datetime(2022, 6, 30))]

# daily base
#start_dates = [datetime.strftime(dt, "%Y-%m-%d") for dt in rrule(DAILY, dtstart=datetime(2022, 1, 1), until=datetime(2022, 1, 10))]
#end_dates = [datetime.strftime(dt, "%Y-%m-%d") for dt in rrule(DAILY, dtstart=datetime(2022, 1, 2), until=datetime(2022, 1, 11))]
dates_list = list(zip(start_dates, end_dates))

# get articles from news pages; inspired by https://blog.finxter.com/analyzing-news-articles-with-newspaper3k-textblob-and-seaborn/ for data acquisition

def get_articles(dates):                         
    news_sites = ['faz.net', 'dw.com', 'sueddeutsche.de', 'taz.de', 'nzz.ch']
    data = []
    article_titles = []
    article_contents = []
    article_urls = []
    article_pubdate = []
    counter = 0 
              
    for site in news_sites:
        print(site)
        # loop through single months to get the urls from a search in google news
        for date1, date2 in dates:
            print("Gets urls from " + str(date1) + "...")
            
            # URL of the Google News RSS with Joe Biden in the search parameter
            main_url = "https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=after:" + date1 + "+before:" + date2 + "+site:" + site + "&ceid=DE:en&hl=de-DE&gl=DE"
            #print(main_url)
            
            # get the results in the RSS and collect the links
            response = requests.get(main_url)
            webpage = response.content
            soup = BeautifulSoup(webpage, features="xml")
            items = soup.find_all('item')
            for item in items:
                link = item.find('link').text
                article_urls.append(link)
                date = item.find('pubDate').text
                article_pubdate.append(date)
        print("Fetched " + str(len(article_urls)) + " urls.")        
        # getting the articles from the news site by calling the gathered url    
    for url in article_urls:
        counter +=1
        if counter % 50 == 0:
            print("Processed " + str(counter) + " articles..." )
               
        # We throw this in a try/except block in case we get a bad link which would kill the program
        try:
        # Newspaper3k to scrape the article text and title
            article = Article(url, language='de')
            article.download()
            article.parse()
            article.nlp()

            article_titles.append(article.title)
            article_contents.append(article.text)
                    
            # If there is a bad link, move on to the next one
        except ArticleException:
            print("There was a bad link: " + url)
            article_titles.append('NaN')
            article_contents.append('NaN')
            pass
    data = {'title': article_titles, 'url': article_urls, 'content': article_contents, 'time': article_pubdate} 

    return(pd.DataFrame(data))

Preprocessing¶

In a second step, some preprocessing is done. First, a check for missing values and double rows is performed. Next, we do some text preprocessing like excluding punctuation, invalid words or numbers. The articles are also tokenized and if specified also stemmed. Lastly, the stopwords are removed. Like this, they are in a format to be further processed.

# preprocessing the content, removing stop words

def preprocess_text(text, stop_words, shouldBeStemmed=False):
    
    # remove punctuations
    text = text.replace(".", "")
    
    # tokenize input
    text = word_tokenize(text)
    
    # exclude "words" without letters (for example numbers) 
    text = [word for word in text if re.search('[a-zA-Z]', word)]
    
    # exclude special characters 
    text = [re.sub('[^\w|-|\"|\s]', '', word) for word in text]
    
    # all lower
    text = [word.lower() for word in text]

    # stemming words for later keyword search
    if shouldBeStemmed:
        ha = ht.HanoverTagger('morphmodel_ger.pgz')
        temp = []
        counter =0
        for word in text:
            temp.append(ha.analyze(word)[0])
        text = temp
    
    # exclude stopwords 
    text = [word for word in text if word not in stop_words]
    
    return ' '.join(text)

# get top ngrams

def get_ngrams(n, data):
    count_vec = CountVectorizer(ngram_range=(n,n))
    count_data = count_vec.fit_transform(data['content'])
    count_values = count_data.toarray().sum(axis=0)
    
    vocs = count_vec.vocabulary_
    df_ngram_counts = pd.DataFrame([(count_values[i],k) for k,i in vocs.items()])
    
    df_ngram_counts = df_ngram_counts.rename(columns={0: 'count', 1: 'bigram'})
    return df_ngram_counts.groupby('bigram').sum().sort_values('count', ascending=False)

Keyword search¶

In a fourth step, an application is included into the data science workflow. A keyword search should be performed. Therefore, a user defined sentence or a question is stated. The tokens in the text bodies are characterized by the tfidf-algorithm to get the relative importance of the tokens for the texts. Also the user defined sentence is analyzed using the same model. In a last step, the cosine similarity between the vector for the questions and all the vectors for the articles is calculated and the result are descendingly ordered printed. The most relevant answers for the question are then presented to the user and the user can read the specific answer to get the article for his question.

Above, the results for the cosine similarity are presented. The first two articles are really about the football team from Frankfurt winning the europe league. So for getting correct recommendations a score of above 40% might be sufficient. For other topics like the war in Ukraine "Russland wird die Ukraine angreifen.", it might not be sufficient as sometimes articles are just loosely connected to the war but deal more with the economical consequences in Germany. These wouldn't be good recommendations but also having a quite high similarity.

Discussion and further approaches¶

Within this small project, a content-based recommender system for news articles has been developed. After a user wrote a statement or a question, the model recommends the most similiar articles from five different newspapers within a given period of time. The model in general works quite good for some tested examples.

What is missing here, is a real testing setting for the model. It should include some bigger amount of sentences which are proven to be true of false and then an evaluation condition like majority of the first five most relevant articles.

It should be also possible to simplify the model by adding the auxilary verbs, like "knnen", "sollen", "mssen" and other verbs which carry no relevant information like "sein", "haben", "sagen", "geben" to the list of stop words to exclude them from the model. Further improvement should be done by expanding the stemming to also take synonyms into account. But before, a subject matter expert should answer the question to which amount the simplification should take place. For example, "Russland marschiert in die Ukraine ein" might be something else than "Russland fhrt Krieg gegen die Ukraine" or "Putin greift die Ukraine an". To some level the three mentioned sentences are synonyms but if we have a stricter view they mean something different.

For deployment there might also be another structure of the project which is faster and cheaper. Like this, all the documents are downloaded at the beginng and then every run again. It would be better to download and then preprocess them once and save them locally in a csv file or similar and just update them.

If you want to try the news search I created a small notebook on binder.com where you can type in your own phrase in code chunk 5 without the need to download and preprocess the data. The underlying data are the articles from January 2020 until June 2022. They are just reimported from a csv-file which is made above after the preprocessing. you can access it here: https://mybinder.org/v2/gh/MaraAcuja/news_search/c72714830d958d50513902a4bd6b494122865793?urlpath=lab%2Ftree%2Fnews_search.ipynb
